Name: John Smith
Age: 58
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, smoking history of 1 pack per day for 30 years
Key Complaints: Abdominal pain, constipation, rectal bleeding, unintentional weight loss of 10 pounds over 2 months.

Name: John Smith
Age: 55
Gender: Male
Occupation: Salesman
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, smoking history of 30 pack-years

Key Complaints: John presents with rectal bleeding and abdominal pain for the past month. He reports a change in bowel habits, including constipation and diarrhea. He also reports unintentional weight loss of 10 pounds over the past 6 months. On physical exam, there is tenderness in the left lower quadrant of the abdomen. A digital rectal exam reveals occult blood in the stool.

Based on John's symptoms and exam findings, colon cancer is suspected. Further imaging and colonoscopy are recommended for diagnosis and staging.

Name: John Smith
Age: 50 years old
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, high cholesterol, occasional heartburn
Key Complaints: Abdominal pain, constipation, blood in stool

John Smith is a 50-year-old Caucasian male who works as a construction worker. He has a past medical history of hypertension, high cholesterol, and occasional heartburn. He presents to the clinic with complaints of abdominal pain, constipation, and blood in his stool. He reports that the symptoms started about two months ago and have been getting progressively worse. He denies any recent weight loss or changes in his bowel habits. Upon further evaluation, a colonoscopy is recommended, which reveals a mass in the colon consistent with colon cancer. John is promptly referred for surgery and further treatment.

Name: John Smith
Age: 55
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: High blood pressure, occasional heartburn, no family history of colon cancer

Key Complaints:
John presents to his primary care physician with complaints of abdominal discomfort and occasional rectal bleeding for the past few weeks. He has also noticed a change in his bowel habits, with more frequent diarrhea alternating with constipation. He denies any significant weight loss or loss of appetite. Upon further questioning, he admits to occasional alcohol use and a high-fat diet. A digital rectal exam reveals a palpable mass in the rectum. Further workup including a colonoscopy confirms the diagnosis of colon cancer.
